               <history>
                  <origin>
                     <origDate notBefore="1700" notAfter="1799">18th century, an earlier period (17th century) cannot be excluded.</origDate>
                     <ref target="#a3">Additional note 3</ref> suggests that the manuscript is related to the <persName ref="ETH1274Betaes">Beta ʾƎsrāʾel</persName> community.
                     <bibl><ptr target="bm:Butts2013Reception"/><citedRange unit="page">5-6</citedRange></bibl> indicates that, contrary to R. Cowley's claim and what may
                     appear at the first glance, the incipit has not been altered (e.g. with the aim of surpressing it, common for Christian manuscripts 
                     acquired and customized by <persName ref="ETH1274Betaes">Beta ʾƎsrāʾel</persName>). However, <ref target="#a3"/>, being an invocation considered
                     typical for <persName ref="ETH1274Betaes">Beta ʾƎsrāʾel</persName>, appears to have been added later. Other features that may be indicative of 
                     the <persName ref="ETH1274Betaes">Beta ʾƎsrāʾel</persName>'s ownership of the manucript have not been addressed yet.   
                  </origin>
                     <provenance>
                    The manuscript was acquired by <persName ref="PRS1071dAbbadi" role="owner">Antoine d'Abbadie</persName>
                      sometime between <date>1840</date> and <date>1848</date>.
                    </provenance>
                  <acquisition>The manuscript entered <placeName ref="INS0303BNF"/> in
                    <date>1902</date>.
                    </acquisition>
               </history>
